Interaction: Certificate

1. Potential Data Repudiation by Cert-Manager  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Cert-Manager claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso i controlli AU-2, AU-7 e AU-11
Short Description:Repudiation threats involve an adversary denying that something happened.

2. Data Flow Sniffing  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Data flowing across Certificate may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. Consider encrypting the data flow.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso il controllo SC-7
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

3. Potential Process Crash or Stop for Cert-Manager  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Cert-Manager crashes, halts, stops or runs slowly; in all cases violating an availability metric.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso il controllo SC-5
Short Description:Denial of Service happens when the process or a datastore is not able to service incoming requests or perform up to spec.

4. Data Flow Certificate Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso i controlli SC-5, SC-7 e SC-8
Short Description:Denial of Service happens when the process or a datastore is not able to service incoming requests or perform up to spec.

5. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Cert-Manager may be able to impersonate the context of Nginx in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:A user subject gains increased capability or privilege by taking advantage of an implementation bug.

6. Elevation by Changing the Execution Flow in Cert-Manager  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:An attacker may pass data into Cert-Manager in order to change the flow of program execution within Cert-Manager to the attacker's choosing.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso i controlli AC-5 e AC-6
Short Description:A user subject gains increased capability or privilege by taking advantage of an implementation bug.

7. Weak Authentication Scheme  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Custom authentication schemes are susceptible to common weaknesses such as weak credential change management, credential equivalence, easily guessable credentials, null credentials, downgrade authentication or a weak credential change management system. Consider the impact and potential mitigations for your custom authentication scheme.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso i controlli IA-2 e IA-5
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

8. Authenticated Data Flow Compromised  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:An attacker can read or modify data transmitted over an authenticated dataflow.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso il controllo SC-7
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

18. Nginx Process Memory Tampered  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:If Nginx is given access to memory, such as shared memory or pointers, or is given the ability to control what Keycloack executes (for example, passing back a function pointer.), then Nginx can tamper with Keycloack. Consider if the function could work with less access to memory, such as passing data rather than pointers. Copy in data provided, and then validate it.
Justification:Viene mitigato attraverso il controllo SC-39
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.
